{"cursor":"9979","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Pairwise comparison' generally refers to any process of comparing entities in\npairs to judge which of each entity is preferred, or has a greater amount of\nsome quantitative property. The method of pairwise comparison is used in the\nscientific study of preferences, attitudes, voting systems, social choice,\npublic choice, and multiagent AI systems. In psychology literature, it is often\nreferred to as 'paired comparison'.\n\nProminent psychometrician L. L. Thurstone first introduced a scientific approach\nto using pairwise comparisons for measurement in 1927, which he referred to as\nthe law of comparative judgment. Thurstone linked this approach to\npsychophysical theory developed by Ernst Heinrich Weber and Gustav Fechner.\nThurstone demonstrated that the method can be used to order items along a\ndimension such as preference or importance using an interval-type scale.\n","linknr":160,"url":"Pairwise_comparison","recorded":1362671214,"links":16,"instances":[],"pdf":["http://www.danko-nikolic.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/09/Nikolic-Transitivity-2007.pdf","http://www.ee.washington.edu/research/guptalab/publications/PairedComparisonTutorialTsukidaGuptaUWTechReport2011.pdf"],"categories":["Psychometrics"],"headings":["Overview","Probabilistic models","Transitivity","Argument for intransitivity of indifference","Preference orders","Applications","See also","References","Further reading"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/e/5/be51d3370172173cf42339a07d1731e9.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/8/5/185dcc051a9d90b6865a49b0db1d0197.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/6/5/865c0c0b4ab0e063e5caa3387c1a8741.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/1/7/817c3617f789353bff00ad8ea7af7bb6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/4/a/a4a46d8c6c35bcf2023ea5c822278375.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/e/f/4efe241f58b7472662372b12074fd121.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/4/f/24f28becfa0d33c285b226a2013cd1a0.png